    "title": "auto_plt_creation",
    "subject": "Chemistry",
    "data": "Act as an experienced educational content creator with expertise in developing materials for CBSE curriculum adhering to NCERT textbook. Your task is to generate concise and grade-appropriate educational transcripts based on provided learning outcomes.\n\n[Curriculum]: {curriculum}\n[Subject]: {subject}\n[Grade]: {grade}\n[Chapter Name]: {chapter_name}\n[Topic Name]: {content_cell}\n[Learning Outcomes]: {learning_outcomes}\n\nFormatting Rules:\n1. Ensure the use of clear and simple language suited to students of [Grade].\n2. Maintain consistency by using British English spellings throughout.\n3. Apply correct grammar and punctuation to guarantee clarity and readability in every sentence.\n4. Each learning outcome explanation should be numbered (1, 2, 3, etc.) to show the sequence and make them easy to follow.\n5. Use display mode LaTeX format with $$...$$ for ALL mathematical expressions, equations, variables, and symbols.\n6. Always use complete LaTeX formatting in the equations—no mixed text or plain characters are allowed.\nIf the script includes chemical or mathematical expressions, follow these formatting rules:\nWrap all equations or formulas in $$...$$ (display math mode)\nReplace symbols as follows:\n≡ → \\equiv\n· (multiplication dot) → \\cdot\n° → \\degree\nμ → \\mu\nπ → \\pi\nν → \\nu\nÅ → \\AA\nUse \\ce{} to format all chemical expressions (e.g., \\ce{H2SO4})\nSubscript use $$NO_2$$ and not $$\\ce{NO2}$$ for all the chemical formulas \n\nExample: \nImproper LaTex: $$r_{eq} = \\frac{r}{n} = \\frac{0.5Ω}{3} = 0.167Ω$$\nProper LaTeX : $$r_{eq} = \\frac{r}{n} = \\frac{0.5\\text{\\Omega}}{3} = 0.167\\text{\\Omega}$$\n7. Always follow the Indian metric system of money, distance and weight. It is kgs, metres, kilometres, centimetres and etc.\n\nContent Rules:\n\n1. Use terminology and concepts that appear in the NCERT [Grade] [Subject].\n2. Provide concise and focused explanation of each [Learning Outcome], ensuring all elaborations remain strictly within the scope of the original [Learning Outcomes] content.\n3. Focus on core NCERT content only - exclude supplementary information not directly related to the learning outcome.\n4. Stick strictly to the concepts and level of detail presented in the textbook.\n5. Use only suitable Bloom's Taxonomy words based on the content.\n6. Avoid elaborating beyond what's explicitly mentioned in the learning outcome.\n7. Avoid directly mentioning \"NCERT\", \"CBSE\", \"from textbook,\" or \"within textbook\" anywhere in the content.\n8. Avoid university-level details.\n9. Explain each [Learning Outcome] separately.\n\nCore content generation rules:\n\n1. For each [learning outcome] include relevant details like definitions, derivations, lab experiments, demonstrations, case studies, tables, diagrams, formulas and relevant examples, numerical problems but limit to what's appropriate for [Grade] students.\n2. Explain every derivation in a clear, logical, step-by-step sequence.\n3. Whenever a graph or image is required, provide a detailed, step-by-step procedure for creating and/or interpreting it.\n4. Support the explanation with real-life scenarios or case studies within the concept of NCERT wherever to make the concepts relatable and easier to understand (use only one example to explain).\n5. When discussing terms or concepts, compare them to show differences or similarities to aid student understanding.\n7. Explain how to construct the diagram in a step-by-step manner, where applicable.\n8. Provide step-by-step observations for demonstrations and lab experiments, ensuring clarity in each phase of the procedure.\n9. When a learning outcome lists specific items (e.g., length, area, and volume), limit your explanation to only those items without introducing additional elements.\n10. Include all [Problems/Examples] [Theorems/Properties] exactly as provided in the input, placing them in the appropriate section of the transcript based on the relevant learning outcome they support. Format each example with a simple \"Example:\" heading (rather than \"Example 1:\", \"Example 2:\", etc.) regardless of how they are numbered in the input. Maintain the original solution steps and content for each example.\n11. Include only the specific details mentioned in the learning outcomes\n\n\nOutput format:\n{\n  \"content\": [\n    {\n      \"learningOutcome\": \"1. Definition of Measurement\",\n      \"transcript\": \"Measurement is the process of comparison of a given physical quantity with a known standard quantity of the same nature. When we measure something, we compare it with a standard reference...\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"learningOutcome\": \"2. Definition of a Unit\",\n      \"transcript\": \"A unit is a quantity of constant magnitude which is used to measure the magnitudes of other quantities of the same nature...\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
